    "John Trapp": "Every tree , &amp;c.] The Hebrews think that the world was created in September, because the fruits were then ripe and ready. \u0395\u03c0\u03b5\u03c7\u03c9 The tree of life also .] A symbolical tree; by the eating of the fruit whereof Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]` should have had Gaius\u2019s prosperity, \"his body should have been in health, as his soul prospered,\" { #3Jo 2 } The tree of knowledge of good and evil .] So called, not because itself either knew, or could cause man to know; but from the event; God forewarning our first parents, that they should know by woeful experience, unless they abstained, what was the worth of good, by the want of it; and what the presence of evil, by the sense of it. In like sort the waters of Meribah, and Kibroth Hattaavah, or the graves of lust, received their names from that which happened in those places.\nVer.\n9. Creditur Aegyptus caruisse iuvantibus arva Imbribus, atque annis sicca fuisse novem. -Ovid. { b } Sen., Nat. Quaest., lib. iv. cap.\n9. I do remember my faults this day. ] Oratio vere aulica, saith Pareus, -a right courtier\u2019s speech. He so relates the history of his imprisonment, that he takes all the blame thereof to himself; gives Pharaoh the full commendation of his justice and clemency. As for Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`, he mentions him to the king, lest, if any else should have done it before him, he should have been disgraced for his silence; but somewhat slenderly, and more for self-respects, than of any good affection to the innocent prisoner; whom he calls a young man, a bondman, and Hebrew; in whose beha lf he neither adviseth, nor entreateth that he may be sent for. So very little is it that Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` oweth to this patron! And such, for most part, are court commendations. There you have \u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03b2\u03bf\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b2\u03bf\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd ; as one said of old, delays and changes good store: every man seeking and serving his own aims and ends; but little minding the good of others, further than subservient to their own.\nVer.\n9. And Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` remembered the dreams. ] Event is the best interpreter of divine oracles The disciples understood not many things at first that our Saviour said to them; as that. #Joh 2:22 12:16 So John `[char_John_Ref]` Baptist\u2019s preaching wrought not for some years after it was delivered, and then it did. { #Joh 10:41,42 } The spouse either heard not, or heeded not that speech of her beloved, \"Open unto me, my sister, my spouse,\" till some while after he was gone. { #So 5:2-6 } Ye are spies. ] This, Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` speaks not, assertive, but tentative; not seriously, but by a covert counsel; not as himself thought, but as the Egyptians suspected; or not absolutely, but conditionally; \"ye are spies,\" unless you prove what ye have spoken. { a } { a } Exploratores deputo homini merito mendacii vestri. -Aug.\nVer.\n9. I will be surety for him. ] Herein he was a type of Christ, that came of him, who is both our surety to God, for the discharge of our debt and duty, and God\u2019s surety to us, for the performance of his promises. { #Heb 7:22 }\nVer.\n9. Every tree, &c.] The Hebrews think that the world was created in September, because the fruits were then ripe and ready. \u0395\u03c0\u03b5\u03c7\u03c9 The tree of life also.] A symbolical tree; by the eating of the fruit whereof Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]` should have had Gaius\u2019s prosperity, \"his body should have been in health, as his soul prospered,\" {#3Jo 2} The tree of knowledge of good and evil.] So called, not because itself either knew, or could cause man to know; but from the event; God forewarning our first parents, that they should know by woeful experience, unless they abstained, what was the worth of good, by the want of it; and what the presence of evil, by the sense of it. In like sort the waters of Meribah, and Kibroth Hattaavah, or the graves of lust, received their names from that which happened in those places.\nVer.\n9. Annon quaererem tibi requiem? -Aben- ezra. {c} Habet inhabitatorem Draconem Apostatam.\u2014Ignat. Epist. ad Philad.\nVer.\n9. Creditur Aegyptus caruisse iuvantibus arva Imbribus, atque annis sicca fuisse novem. -Ovid. {b} Sen., Nat. Quaest., lib. iv. cap.\n9. I do remember my faults this day.] Oratio vere aulica, saith Pareus, -a right courtier\u2019s speech. He so relates the history of his imprisonment, that he takes all the blame thereof to himself; gives Pharaoh the full commendation of his justice and clemency. As for Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`, he mentions him to the king, lest, if any else should have done it before him, he should have been disgraced for his silence; but somewhat slenderly, and more for self-respects, than of any good affection to the innocent prisoner; whom he calls a young man, a bondman, and Hebrew; in whose behalf he neither adviseth, nor entreateth that he may be sent for. So very little is it that Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` oweth to this patron! And such, for most part, are court commendations. There you have \u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03b2\u03bf\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b2\u03bf\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd; as one said of old, delays and changes good store: every man seeking and serving his own aims and ends; but little minding the good of others, further than subservient to their own.\nVer.\n9. And Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` remembered the dreams.] Event is the best interpreter of divine oracles The disciples understood not many [v_Jhn_2_22] things at first that our Saviour said to them; as that. #Joh 2:22 12:16 So John `[char_John_Ref]` Baptist\u2019s preaching wrought not for some years after [v_Jhn_10_41] it was delivered, and then it did. {#Joh 10:41,42} The spouse either heard not, or heeded not that speech of her beloved, \"Open unto me, my sister, my spouse,\" till some while after he was gone. {#So 5:2-6} Ye are spies.] This, Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` speaks not, assertive, but tentative; not seriously, but by a covert counsel; not as himself thought, but as the Egyptians suspected; or not absolutely, but conditionally; \"ye are spies,\" unless you prove what ye have spoken. {a} {a} Exploratores deputo homini merito mendacii vestri. -Aug.\nVer.\n9. I will be surety for him.] Herein he was a type of Christ, that came of him, who is both our surety to God, for the discharge of our debt and duty, and God\u2019s surety to us, for the performance of [v_Heb_7_22] his promises. {#Heb 7:22}\nVer.\n9. And I will give thee thy wages. ] The nurse expects not her pay from the child, but from the parents. Ministers, in case their people prove unkind or unthankful, must look up.\nVer.\n9. And I will give thee thy wages.] The nurse expects not her pay from the child, but from the parents. Ministers, in case their people prove unkind or unthankful, must look up.\nVer.",
